{"parse":{"title":"Pattern Blocks","pageid":7904749,"revid":849910311,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Plastic_pattern_blocks.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Plastic_pattern_blocks.JPG/220px-Plastic_pattern_blocks.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"145\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Plastic_pattern_blocks.JPG/330px-Plastic_pattern_blocks.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Plastic_pattern_blocks.JPG/440px-Plastic_pattern_blocks.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"2033\" data-file-height=\"1339\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Plastic_pattern_blocks.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Plastic Pattern Blocks</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Pattern Blocks</b> are one of the <a href=\"/wiki/Mathematical_manipulatives\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mathematical manipulatives\">mathematical manipulatives</a> developed in the 1960s by <a href=\"/wiki/Education_Development_Center\" title=\"Education Development Center\">Education Development Center</a> as part of their Elementary Science Study project.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> They allow children to see how shapes can be decomposed into other shapes, and introduce children to ideas of <a href=\"/wiki/Tessellation\" title=\"Tessellation\">tilings</a>. The Pattern Blocks includes multiple copies of six shapes:\n</p>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Equilateral_triangle\" title=\"Equilateral triangle\">Equilateral triangle</a> (Green)</li>\n<li>60\u00b0 <a href=\"/wiki/Rhombus\" title=\"Rhombus\">rhombus</a> (2 triangles) (Blue) that can be matched with two of the green triangles</li>\n<li>30\u00b0 Narrow rhombus (Beige) with the same side-length as the green triangle</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Trapezoid\" title=\"Trapezoid\">Trapezoid</a> (half hexagon or 3 triangles) (Red) that can be matched with three of the green triangles</li>\n<li>Regular <a href=\"/wiki/Hexagon\" title=\"Hexagon\">Hexagon</a> (6 triangles) (Yellow) that can be matched with six of the green triangles</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Square_(geometry)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Square (geometry)\">Square</a> (Orange) with the same side-length as the green triangle</li></ul>\n<p>All the angles are multiples of 30\u00b0 (1/12 of a circle): 30\u00b0 (1\u00d7), 60\u00b0 (2\u00d7), 90\u00b0 (3\u00d7), 120\u00b0 (4\u00d7), and 150\u00b0 (5\u00d7).\n</p><p>Pattern Blocks are used for creative design\u2014\"floor\" tiling patterns; pictures of animals, flowers, boats, rockets, and so on\u2014and for mathematical purposes other than geometric (e.g., introducing ideas of fractions and proportionality).\n</p><p>An example of their use is given by Meha Agrawal: \"Starting from the center, I would add tier after tier of blocks to build my pattern \u2014 it was an iterative process, because if something didn't look aesthetically appealing or fit correctly, it would require peeling off a layer and reevaluating ways to fix it. The best part was the gratification I received when my creation was complete. Though individually boring, collectively these blocks produced an intricate masterpiece that brought art and math, big-picture and detail, simplicity and complexity closer together\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pattern_Blocks_and_Deci-Blocks.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Pattern_Blocks_and_Deci-Blocks.jpg/220px-Pattern_Blocks_and_Deci-Blocks.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Pattern_Blocks_and_Deci-Blocks.jpg/330px-Pattern_Blocks_and_Deci-Blocks.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Pattern_Blocks_and_Deci-Blocks.jpg/440px-Pattern_Blocks_and_Deci-Blocks.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"4896\" data-file-height=\"3672\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pattern_Blocks_and_Deci-Blocks.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Pattern Blocks and Deci-Blocks</div></div></div>\n<p>A number of compatible shapes that extend pattern blocks are commercially available. Two sets of \"Fractional Pattern Blocks\" exist: both with two blocks.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The first has a pink double hexagon and a black chevron equivalent to four triangles. The second has a brown half-trapezoid and a pink half-triangle. Another set, Deci-Blocks, is made up of six shapes, equivalent to four, five, seven, eight, nine and ten triangles respectively.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Examples\">Examples</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pattern_Blocks&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Examples\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<table class=\"wikitable\">\n<caption>Example constructions\n</caption>\n<tbody><tr>\n<th colspan=\"3\">Regular <a href=\"/wiki/Dodecagon\" title=\"Dodecagon\">dodecagons</a>\n</th>\n<th><a href=\"/wiki/Isotoxal_figure\" title=\"Isotoxal figure\">Isotoxal</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Octagon\" title=\"Octagon\">octagon</a>\n</th></tr>\n<tr>\n<td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Wooden_pattern_blocks_dodecagon.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Wooden pattern blocks dodecagon.JPG\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Wooden_pattern_blocks_dodecagon.JPG/160px-Wooden_pattern_blocks_dodecagon.JPG\" width=\"160\" height=\"154\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Wooden_pattern_blocks_dodecagon.JPG/240px-Wooden_pattern_blocks_dodecagon.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Wooden_pattern_blocks_dodecagon.JPG/320px-Wooden_pattern_blocks_dodecagon.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"1419\" data-file-height=\"1362\" /></a>\n</td>\n<td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Rhombic_dissected_dodecagon12.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Rhombic dissected dodecagon12.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Rhombic_dissected_dodecagon12.svg/160px-Rhombic_dissected_dodecagon12.svg.png\" width=\"160\" height=\"160\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Rhombic_dissected_dodecagon12.svg/240px-Rhombic_dissected_dodecagon12.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Rhombic_dissected_dodecagon12.svg/320px-Rhombic_dissected_dodecagon12.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1000\" data-file-height=\"1000\" /></a>\n</td>\n<td><a href=\"/wiki/File:12-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"12-gon rhombic dissection-size2.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/12-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg/160px-12-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg.png\" width=\"160\" height=\"160\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/12-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg/240px-12-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/12-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg/320px-12-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1000\" data-file-height=\"1000\" /></a>\n</td>\n<td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Isotoxal_8-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Isotoxal 8-gon rhombic dissection-size2.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Isotoxal_8-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg/160px-Isotoxal_8-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg.png\" width=\"160\" height=\"160\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Isotoxal_8-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg/240px-Isotoxal_8-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Isotoxal_8-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg/320px-Isotoxal_8-gon_rhombic_dissection-size2.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1000\" data-file-height=\"1000\" /></a>\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pattern_Blocks&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.picciotto.org/math-ed/angles/index.html\">Picciotto Math Education</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">McFarland, Matt (9 December 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/innovations/wp/2013/12/09/the-childhood-toys-that-inspired-female-engineers-and-scientists/\">\"The childhood toys that inspired female engineers and scientists\"</a>. <i>The Washington Post</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">10 December</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Washington+Post&amp;rft.atitle=The+childhood+toys+that+inspired+female+engineers+and+scientists&amp;rft.date=2013-12-09&amp;rft.aulast=McFarland&amp;rft.aufirst=Matt&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fblogs%2Finnovations%2Fwp%2F2013%2F12%2F09%2Fthe-childhood-toys-that-in